[[File:Eyeshadow cardinalfish at Shaab Mahmud.JPG|thumb|left|''P. exostigma'' from [[Red Sea]], [[Egypt]]]]

'''''Pristiapogon exostigma''''', also known as '''Eyeshadow cardinalfish''' or '''oneline cardinalfish''', is a small (max length is 11&nbsp;cm) pale [[ray-finned fish]] from the [[Family (biology)|family]] [[Apogonidae]], the [[cardinalfish]]es with light-ended black stripe ending in black spot above centre of stripe.
<ref>{{cite book | title=Coral reef guide. Red Sea | first1=Ewald | last1=Lieske | first2=Robert | last2=Myers | year=2004 | page=88 | isbn=9780007741731}}</ref>
<ref>[http://www.marinespecies.org/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&id=712695 WoRMS - World Register of Marine Species - Pristiapogon exostigma (Jordan & Starks, 1906)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
<ref name = FishBase>{{FishBase|genus=Pristiapogon|species= exostigma|year=2014|month=February}}</ref> It has an [[Indo-Pacific]] range which extends from the [[Red Sea]] to the [[Line Islands]] and [[Mangareva Islands]] and south to northern Australia and north to the [[Ryukyu Islands]].<ref name = FishBase/>

This species spends the day sheltering under rock ledges.<ref name = FoA>{{cite web | author = Bray, D.J. | year = 2017 | title = ''Pristiapogon exostigma'' | work = Fishes of Australia | accessdate = 23 Sep 2018 | url = http://fishesofaustralia.net.au/home/species/3251 | publisher = Museums Victoria}}</ref> They can be found among isolated coral heads in the silty sheltered by reefs. It is a solitary and rather rare, [[Nocturnality|nocturnal]] species which feeds on fishes and invertebrates. They are [[Mouthbrooding|mouthbrooders]] who form pairs when courting.<ref name = FishBase/>






